1
00:00:01,481 --> 00:00:04,881
MAN ON COMPUTER: So today I want to talk
about the greatest woman I ever met.

2
00:00:05,881 --> 00:00:10,321
Smart, funny, caring, special.

3
00:00:10,721 --> 00:00:11,841
Proper special.

4
00:00:13,281 --> 00:00:15,921
Er, where do I start? (LAUGHS)

5
00:00:16,041 --> 00:00:17,721
Okay, er...

6
00:00:20,841 --> 00:00:22,121
I've mentioned this on here before,

7
00:00:23,921 --> 00:00:27,441
I'm pretty much not an idiot.
I'm actually a capable guy, considering.

8
00:00:28,801 --> 00:00:32,081
But I'm 189, and because of the thing
I told you before

9
00:00:33,041 --> 00:00:34,921
I can't yet ride a bike.

10
00:00:36,321 --> 00:00:37,321
(LAUGHS)

11
00:00:40,641 --> 00:00:41,841
Who says you can't?

12
00:00:42,001 --> 00:00:43,801
Me, Nan. We keep trying this.

13
00:00:43,921 --> 00:00:46,201
And we'll go on trying until it's done.

14
00:00:46,281 --> 00:00:48,441
-(SIGHS)
-Now, keep your eye on Granddad.

15
00:00:50,761 --> 00:00:53,401
-You mean Graham?
-Keep your eye on Graham then.

16
00:00:54,001 --> 00:00:58,441
Three, two, one, go!

17
00:00:58,881 --> 00:01:01,321
Go on! (LAUGHS)

18
00:01:03,281 --> 00:01:05,401
Go on, Ryan.

19
00:01:06,761 --> 00:01:08,521
You're doing it, mate!

20
00:01:10,001 --> 00:01:11,721
(GROANS AND SIGHS)

21
00:01:16,761 --> 00:01:18,041
-(GRUNTS)
-Nearly.

22
00:01:19,521 --> 00:01:20,761
No, not nearly.

23
00:01:20,841 --> 00:01:22,841
I'm sick of coming up here,
I'm sick of falling,

24
00:01:23,721 --> 00:01:25,401
and I'm sick of this stupid bike.

25
00:01:27,601 --> 00:01:30,321
Ryan Sinclair, don't you dare!

26
00:01:30,561 --> 00:01:32,561
-(GRUNTS)
-(BIKE THUDS)

27
00:01:38,401 --> 00:01:39,881
(SIGHS)

28
00:01:40,401 --> 00:01:42,561
Mate, you rode it for a second.

29
00:01:42,801 --> 00:01:44,681
Can you stop calling me "mate"?

30
00:01:46,801 --> 00:01:48,081
Anyway, a second's not enough.

31
00:01:48,281 --> 00:01:50,761
You'll do it if you keep on trying.

32
00:01:52,161 --> 00:01:53,801
I just want to make you proud.

33
00:01:54,001 --> 00:01:56,361
You make me proud every day.

34
00:01:58,001 --> 00:01:59,761
Anyway, you're on your own
getting that bike

35
00:01:59,841 --> 00:02:01,521
because our train leaves in 20 minutes.

36
00:02:02,201 --> 00:02:03,921
Come on, love.

37
00:02:23,401 --> 00:02:24,961
(SIGHS)

38
00:02:31,041 --> 00:02:33,281
(SIGHS) Oh, so...

39
00:02:35,921 --> 00:02:38,361
-(SIGHS DEEPLY)
- (ELECTRICITY BUZZES)

40
00:02:44,081 --> 00:02:47,681
(BUZZING CONTINUES)

41
00:03:16,161 --> 00:03:18,001
-(BUZZING INTENSIFIES)
-(GROANS)

42
00:03:45,441 --> 00:03:47,481
(YELPS IN PAIN)

43
00:03:51,841 --> 00:03:56,481
Hi, er, police, maybe.

44
00:03:57,721 --> 00:03:59,241
She smashed it with a hammer.

45
00:03:59,321 --> 00:04:01,121
Because you keyed my nearside door!

46
00:04:01,201 --> 00:04:02,681
Because you parked in my spot!

47
00:04:02,841 --> 00:04:05,681
It's not your spot, there are no spots.

48
00:04:05,761 --> 00:04:07,681
Ladies, please!

49
00:04:09,801 --> 00:04:12,801
Thank you.
Can I suggest a simple solution?

50
00:04:13,121 --> 00:04:15,201
You pay for her cracked window,
you pay for her scratched door

51
00:04:15,281 --> 00:04:17,401
and we all agree that parking around
here is a nightmare

52
00:04:17,481 --> 00:04:19,521
but that grown-ups really shouldn't need
to call the police

53
00:04:19,601 --> 00:04:21,241
to sort it out for them.

54
00:04:23,521 --> 00:04:25,001
Now, if we're all agreed on that,

55
00:04:25,121 --> 00:04:27,041
there's no need for me
to take any further police action

56
00:04:27,121 --> 00:04:29,641
and we can all get on with our lives.
What do you reckon?

57
00:04:31,481 --> 00:04:35,001
I'm just saying I am capable
of more than parking disputes.

58
00:04:35,961 --> 00:04:37,961
MAN ON PHONE:
And I keep telling you, don't run

59
00:04:38,241 --> 00:04:40,201
before you can walk.
You're a probationer, Yaz.

60
00:04:40,521 --> 00:04:42,441
-Learn the basics.
-I want to do more.

61
00:04:43,241 --> 00:04:45,801
Can you not get them to give me
something that will test me?

62
00:04:45,881 --> 00:04:47,361
Something a bit different.

63
00:04:49,921 --> 00:04:53,561
There is something that just came in,
if you want different.

64
00:05:00,441 --> 00:05:01,961
And you say you just found it here?

65
00:05:02,041 --> 00:05:04,481
No. I said it appeared. Out of nowhere.

66
00:05:04,601 --> 00:05:06,321
-Right.
-I swear, this isn't a prank.

67
00:05:06,401 --> 00:05:07,641
I came down here to get my bike.

68
00:05:07,721 --> 00:05:09,761
-And where's your bike?
-In that tree.

69
00:05:10,201 --> 00:05:11,561
Name, sir?

70
00:05:12,401 --> 00:05:13,401
(SIGHS)

71
00:05:13,481 --> 00:05:14,481
Ryan Sinclair.

72
00:05:15,961 --> 00:05:18,321
Wait, Redlands Primary?

73
00:05:19,001 --> 00:05:20,961
-Yeah!
-Yasmin Khan.

74
00:05:21,481 --> 00:05:23,641
-Oh, my God! Yaz!
-(LAUGHS) Uh-huh.

75
00:05:23,801 --> 00:05:25,041
-Wow!
-I know.

76
00:05:26,441 --> 00:05:29,201
-Look at you. You're a fed?
-Yeah.

77
00:05:29,921 --> 00:05:31,001
-We don't call it that.
-Oh.

78
00:05:31,241 --> 00:05:33,561
I'm still training.
Second year of probation.

79
00:05:33,681 --> 00:05:35,121
What about you. What are you up to?

80
00:05:35,641 --> 00:05:36,721
Warehouse worker.

81
00:05:36,921 --> 00:05:39,761
Oh, right. Like it?

82
00:05:40,401 --> 00:05:44,081
Hate it. It's cash while I study
for my NVQ. I'm trying to be a mechanic.

83
00:05:44,921 --> 00:05:46,161
That's good.

84
00:05:48,881 --> 00:05:50,681
You have to take this away, though.
Seriously.

85
00:05:50,761 --> 00:05:52,921
It's going to be dark in a minute.
You can't dump this here.

86
00:05:53,001 --> 00:05:56,481
-I didn't! I can't even lift it!
-Oh, come on, Ryan! It's me.

87
00:05:56,561 --> 00:05:57,961
-Touch it.
-What?

88
00:06:00,881 --> 00:06:02,361
(INHALES SHARPLY)

89
00:06:06,401 --> 00:06:09,361
-(GASPS)
-See? It's freezing.

90
00:06:11,961 --> 00:06:13,121
(INHALES DEEPLY)

91
00:06:20,201 --> 00:06:22,721
WOMAN ON P.A.:
The next station is Grindleford.

92
00:06:22,801 --> 00:06:24,601
Do you ever think he's going
to call me granddad?

93
00:06:24,681 --> 00:06:26,001
Give him time.

94
00:06:26,081 --> 00:06:27,361
Three years we've been married.

95
00:06:27,481 --> 00:06:29,241
And you've never been happier.

96
00:06:29,721 --> 00:06:32,161
Grindleford is the next station stop.

97
00:06:32,561 --> 00:06:35,081
-Can't keep his hands off me, love.
-Behave yourself.

98
00:06:35,201 --> 00:06:36,201
(WHISPERS) Never.

99
00:06:36,721 --> 00:06:37,721
(LAUGHS)

100
00:06:40,681 --> 00:06:42,121
(ELECTRICITY BUZZING)

101
00:06:43,281 --> 00:06:44,921
- (ELECTRICITY SURGING)
-(SCREAMS)

102
00:06:45,201 --> 00:06:46,441
(PASSENGERS GRUNTING)

103
00:06:47,321 --> 00:06:49,801
-(SHARP RINGING)
-(PEOPLE SIGHING)

104
00:06:52,641 --> 00:06:54,441
-Are you all right, love?
-I think so.

105
00:06:54,521 --> 00:06:55,521
Yeah.

106
00:06:56,041 --> 00:06:57,641
What just happened?

107
00:06:57,721 --> 00:07:00,441
-Where are you going?
-Just having a look.

108
00:07:03,721 --> 00:07:04,761
(SIGHS)

109
00:07:12,161 --> 00:07:14,081
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

110
00:07:16,081 --> 00:07:17,481
- (ELECTRICITY BUZZES)
-(MAN SCREAMS)

111
00:07:18,081 --> 00:07:19,281
What are you doing?

112
00:07:19,361 --> 00:07:21,201
Don't go on the track, it could be live!

113
00:07:21,401 --> 00:07:23,121
-MAN: Get off of there!
-(WOMAN SCREAMS)

114
00:07:26,201 --> 00:07:27,921
GRACE: Graham, the door's just locked!

115
00:07:28,161 --> 00:07:30,081
We're shut in. I can't get them open!

116
00:07:34,081 --> 00:07:35,241
Something's wrong.

117
00:07:48,121 --> 00:07:50,321
I think something's
coming down the train.

118
00:07:53,841 --> 00:07:55,881
(ELECTRICITY BUZZES)

119
00:07:56,521 --> 00:07:58,001
Right, get away from the door!

120
00:07:58,081 --> 00:08:00,041
Grace, get to the back of the carriage!
Get to the back!

121
00:08:05,121 --> 00:08:07,081
(PANTING AND GRUNTS)

122
00:08:08,921 --> 00:08:11,081
-(MOBILE RINGING)
-Wait one sec.

123
00:08:13,601 --> 00:08:15,001
-Hiya, Nan.
-GRACE ON PHONE: Ryan, love?

124
00:08:15,641 --> 00:08:17,481
Our train stopped between
Hathersage and Grindleford,

125
00:08:17,561 --> 00:08:19,561
and something really weird's
going on... (VOICE DISTORTING)

126
00:08:19,681 --> 00:08:21,041
-(MOBILE BEEPING)
-Everything all right?

127
00:08:23,281 --> 00:08:24,281
Nan!

128
00:08:24,601 --> 00:08:25,601
(SIREN WAILING)

129
00:08:26,801 --> 00:08:28,361
GRAHAM: Grace, get back.

130
00:08:36,521 --> 00:08:39,041
-(EXPLOSION)
-(WOMAN SCREAMS)

131
00:08:39,521 --> 00:08:40,881
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

132
00:08:44,801 --> 00:08:46,361
(ELECTRICITY BUZZES)

133
00:08:55,321 --> 00:08:56,601
What is it?

134
00:08:56,961 --> 00:08:58,041
I've no idea.

135
00:09:02,961 --> 00:09:04,521
(MUTTERING INDISTINCTLY)

136
00:09:04,761 --> 00:09:06,201
Oh, come on.

137
00:09:06,841 --> 00:09:08,401
(WHIMPERING)

138
00:09:09,561 --> 00:09:11,201
(WOMAN SCREAMING)

139
00:09:17,161 --> 00:09:18,561
(PANTING)

140
00:09:20,481 --> 00:09:22,081
(INHALES SHARPLY) What?

141
00:09:32,601 --> 00:09:34,441
(PANTING) Should buy us a few seconds.

142
00:09:36,961 --> 00:09:38,561
Oh, yeah. Long story.

143
00:09:38,761 --> 00:09:40,041
Tell you later. Doors?

144
00:09:40,561 --> 00:09:42,921
-Locked shut.
-We'll see about that.

145
00:09:44,241 --> 00:09:45,441
No Sonic.

146
00:09:46,921 --> 00:09:48,921
Empty pockets. (GROANS)

147
00:09:49,001 --> 00:09:51,281
-I hate empty pockets.
-It's coming back!

148
00:09:54,601 --> 00:09:56,081
What are you?

149
00:09:56,761 --> 00:10:00,321
Whoa. Okay. Don't like questions.
More the private type. I get that.

150
00:10:04,721 --> 00:10:07,281
(WHIMPERING)

151
00:10:07,481 --> 00:10:08,681
Get away from me!

152
00:10:09,081 --> 00:10:13,721
All of you, stay very still.

153
00:10:14,081 --> 00:10:15,761
He's going to kill us.

154
00:10:16,041 --> 00:10:17,801
He could have done that already.

155
00:10:19,281 --> 00:10:20,281
RYAN: Nan!

156
00:10:20,401 --> 00:10:21,761
Ryan, stay away!

157
00:10:22,921 --> 00:10:24,121
Oh, my God.

158
00:10:24,561 --> 00:10:26,201
-(ALL SCREAMING)
- (ELECTRICITY BUZZING)

159
00:10:31,641 --> 00:10:34,721
You three, relax, but stay put.
I'll check the rest of the train.

160
00:10:35,361 --> 00:10:36,841
Fat lot of use you two were.

161
00:10:37,441 --> 00:10:38,441
Hey!

162
00:10:38,521 --> 00:10:40,521
Hold on there please, madam,
I need you to do as I say.

163
00:10:40,601 --> 00:10:41,601
This could be a potential

164
00:10:41,721 --> 00:10:43,561
-crime scene, madam.
-Why are you calling me "madam"?

165
00:10:43,641 --> 00:10:44,961
Because you're a woman.

166
00:10:45,641 --> 00:10:47,641
Am I? Does it suit me?

167
00:10:47,881 --> 00:10:49,161
-What?
-Oh, yeah!

168
00:10:49,841 --> 00:10:51,161
I remember.

169
00:10:51,241 --> 00:10:53,841
Sorry, half an hour ago
I was a white-haired Scotsman.

170
00:10:54,161 --> 00:10:56,401
-When's the next train due?
-This is the last one back.

171
00:10:56,481 --> 00:10:58,481
But the doors are locked.
How did you both get in?

172
00:10:58,561 --> 00:11:00,721
-Driver's window was smashed in.
-What's your name?

173
00:11:01,001 --> 00:11:02,601
PC Khan, Hallamshire Police.

174
00:11:02,721 --> 00:11:03,961
Name, not title.

175
00:11:04,041 --> 00:11:05,041
Yasmin Khan.

176
00:11:05,121 --> 00:11:07,241
Yaz to my friends.
Can I have your name, please?

177
00:11:07,321 --> 00:11:08,321
When I can remember it.

178
00:11:08,441 --> 00:11:10,721
-You don't know your own name?
-Of course I know it.

179
00:11:10,801 --> 00:11:13,401
I just can't remember it.
It's right there on the tip of my...

180
00:11:14,681 --> 00:11:15,841
Er, what's that?

181
00:11:16,881 --> 00:11:18,601
-Tongue?
-Tongue!

182
00:11:18,881 --> 00:11:20,521
Smart boy. Biology.

183
00:11:20,681 --> 00:11:22,121
What did she call you? Ryan?

184
00:11:22,561 --> 00:11:23,761
Yeah, Ryan Sinclair.

185
00:11:24,201 --> 00:11:25,881
Good name. Are you a doctor, Ryan?

186
00:11:26,321 --> 00:11:27,601
-No.
-Shame.

187
00:11:28,241 --> 00:11:29,481
I'm looking for a doctor.

188
00:11:33,121 --> 00:11:34,881
Power. Lights.

189
00:11:36,281 --> 00:11:37,281
Doors.

190
00:11:38,401 --> 00:11:39,601
Poor woman.

191
00:11:39,921 --> 00:11:42,001
That thing must have killed her
as it came through.

192
00:11:42,081 --> 00:11:43,361
Why's that?

193
00:11:43,481 --> 00:11:45,241
It didn't kill anyone else.

194
00:11:45,601 --> 00:11:48,441
Looks more like she died of shock
when he smashed through the window.

195
00:11:48,841 --> 00:11:51,041
Either way, a woman has died here.

196
00:11:51,281 --> 00:11:53,001
But no more creatures.

197
00:11:53,241 --> 00:11:54,881
And no other passengers left on board.

198
00:11:54,961 --> 00:11:56,281
Let's get back to the others.

199
00:11:57,201 --> 00:12:00,641
Wait. Can you stop, please?
This could be a major incident.

200
00:12:00,721 --> 00:12:01,921
I'm the one in charge here.

201
00:12:02,041 --> 00:12:03,081
What are you going to do?

202
00:12:03,161 --> 00:12:05,121
-Call it in to my station.
-What are you going to tell them?

203
00:12:05,201 --> 00:12:06,601
-The facts.
-Which are?

204
00:12:07,001 --> 00:12:09,401
-The train was attacked.
-By what?

205
00:12:10,241 --> 00:12:12,401
I need to take a look at CCTV footage.

206
00:12:12,521 --> 00:12:16,481
And why do you need to check CCTV
when we all saw it with our own eyes?

207
00:12:16,601 --> 00:12:18,921
Was it an alien?
Because it looked like an alien to me.

208
00:12:19,001 --> 00:12:21,121
-YASMIN: Oh, come on.
-What, you think he's wrong?

209
00:12:21,201 --> 00:12:23,601
-No, I don't know, but...
-But you're worried about

210
00:12:23,681 --> 00:12:24,841
how you will explain all this

211
00:12:24,921 --> 00:12:27,441
to a superior officer
who won't believe you.

212
00:12:27,721 --> 00:12:28,721
I can't not report it.

213
00:12:28,961 --> 00:12:32,521
You could hold off until we get
the answers to the bigger questions.

214
00:12:32,641 --> 00:12:34,521
-Which are?
-"What was it?

215
00:12:35,081 --> 00:12:36,961
"Why is it here? Where's it going next?"

216
00:12:37,081 --> 00:12:40,081
And most importantly,
"How do we stop it?"

217
00:12:40,241 --> 00:12:42,441
Because whatever it is,
I don't think it's done.

218
00:12:42,801 --> 00:12:44,241
Come on, Ryan. Come on, Yaz.

219
00:12:44,361 --> 00:12:46,481
I'm calling you Yaz
because we're friends now.

220
00:12:49,601 --> 00:12:52,001
It's, um, Karl Wright.

221
00:12:52,401 --> 00:12:54,441
Er, middle name's Brian.

222
00:12:54,681 --> 00:12:57,401
52 Northover Street.

223
00:12:57,641 --> 00:12:58,841
Telephone number?

224
00:12:58,961 --> 00:13:00,001
Right, then, troops.

225
00:13:00,081 --> 00:13:02,361
No, not troops. Team. Gang.

226
00:13:02,921 --> 00:13:03,921
Fam?

227
00:13:04,201 --> 00:13:05,401
I'm distracting myself.

228
00:13:05,521 --> 00:13:07,441
You came crashing through that roof.

229
00:13:07,681 --> 00:13:09,761
I was thrown out of my TARDIS.

230
00:13:10,801 --> 00:13:11,801
Oh!

231
00:13:12,721 --> 00:13:14,281
I've lost my TARDIS.

232
00:13:15,841 --> 00:13:18,721
It was exploding
and then it dematerialised.

233
00:13:20,441 --> 00:13:22,041
Don't panic. Not the end of the world.

234
00:13:22,161 --> 00:13:24,921
Well, it could be the end of the world,
but one thing at a time.

235
00:13:25,281 --> 00:13:27,321
Are we supposed to understand
anything you're saying?

236
00:13:27,521 --> 00:13:30,321
-She thinks that thing is an alien.
-GRAHAM: Don't be daft.

237
00:13:30,401 --> 00:13:31,801
There's no such thing as aliens.

238
00:13:31,961 --> 00:13:34,601
Anyway, even if there was, they ain't
gonna be on a train in Sheffield.

239
00:13:34,681 --> 00:13:36,801
Why not? I'm alien and I'm here.

240
00:13:38,001 --> 00:13:39,241
Grace, we're going.

241
00:13:39,441 --> 00:13:40,521
No, we're not.

242
00:13:40,641 --> 00:13:43,921
-She just saved our lives.
-Don't be scared.

243
00:13:44,041 --> 00:13:46,081
All of this is new to you
and new can be scary.

244
00:13:46,161 --> 00:13:47,881
Now, we all want answers.

245
00:13:47,961 --> 00:13:49,961
Stick with me, you might get some.

246
00:13:50,481 --> 00:13:53,281
Actually, erm, I don't want answers.

247
00:13:53,361 --> 00:13:55,361
I just want to get to work
and forget all about this.

248
00:13:56,601 --> 00:13:58,281
If that's all right with everyone.

249
00:13:58,761 --> 00:14:02,041
Even if it isn't, thank you.

250
00:14:04,441 --> 00:14:07,201
-Would you like me to...
-No, thank you.

251
00:14:07,721 --> 00:14:11,601
I, er, just want to be on my own.
I'lLl walk.

252
00:14:11,761 --> 00:14:12,761
I need the air.

253
00:14:14,041 --> 00:14:15,641
And I'm with him.

254
00:14:15,721 --> 00:14:17,281
We don't get aliens in Sheffield.

255
00:14:19,041 --> 00:14:21,121
I think he's still in shock. Bless him.

256
00:14:22,921 --> 00:14:24,441
Obvious question,

257
00:14:24,521 --> 00:14:27,241
but has anyone noticed anything else
out of the ordinary tonight?

258
00:14:32,801 --> 00:14:35,281
I'm gonna be in such trouble
if they find out I was there.

259
00:14:35,361 --> 00:14:37,041
Can we have the lights and siren on?

260
00:14:37,121 --> 00:14:39,881
No! I shouldn't be doing any of this.

261
00:14:39,961 --> 00:14:41,401
So you three know each other?

262
00:14:41,481 --> 00:14:43,201
-I'm his nan, Graham's my husband.
-Ah.

263
00:14:43,321 --> 00:14:44,401
Second husband.

264
00:14:44,601 --> 00:14:45,961
And you two know each other.

265
00:14:46,041 --> 00:14:47,441
Yeah. Yaz and I were at school together.

266
00:14:47,601 --> 00:14:49,801
-Huh.
-Not Yasmin Khan?

267
00:14:49,881 --> 00:14:51,081
Hello, Ryan's nan.

268
00:14:51,201 --> 00:14:53,161
Haven't you done
well for yourself, love?

269
00:14:53,241 --> 00:14:55,041
And you say you just found it there,
this thing?

270
00:14:55,121 --> 00:14:56,201
Yeah, pretty much.

271
00:14:56,801 --> 00:14:59,481
-I took pictures.
-DOCTOR: (GASPS) Good lad.

272
00:15:00,641 --> 00:15:01,881
That's exciting.

273
00:15:01,961 --> 00:15:04,601
No. Not exciting. What do I mean?

274
00:15:05,361 --> 00:15:07,401
Worrying. Fast as you can, Yaz.

275
00:15:13,281 --> 00:15:14,481
RYAN: There's my bike.

276
00:15:14,921 --> 00:15:16,161
Why's it in a tree?

277
00:15:16,761 --> 00:15:18,521
We were up top and I chucked it over.

278
00:15:18,641 --> 00:15:20,401
He gets cross because he can't ride it.

279
00:15:20,481 --> 00:15:21,601
We're giving him lessons.

280
00:15:21,721 --> 00:15:23,841
He's got dyspraxia.
It's a coordination disorder.

281
00:15:23,921 --> 00:15:25,081
Anyway, enough about me.

282
00:15:26,321 --> 00:15:28,001
The tree's to the left,
so it should be...

283
00:15:30,041 --> 00:15:31,321
YASMIN: It was definitely there.

284
00:15:34,361 --> 00:15:35,961
So where's it gone?

285
00:16:32,761 --> 00:16:36,121
Rahul, if you're all right about that,
should we not tell someone?

286
00:16:38,361 --> 00:16:39,841
What good would that do?

287
00:16:41,401 --> 00:16:42,961
I'm worried for you, mate.

288
00:16:45,281 --> 00:16:46,641
I finally got it.

289
00:16:49,241 --> 00:16:51,681
Go on, mate. Have a pint on me.

290
00:16:52,241 --> 00:16:53,641
I'll see you Monday.
Pick you up at 8:00.

291
00:16:56,041 --> 00:16:57,161
(BREATH TREMBLES)

292
00:17:14,521 --> 00:17:16,281
-(CAMERA BEEPS)
-(SIGHS)

293
00:17:41,921 --> 00:17:45,801
Two weird things, one city, same night.
Makes me nervous.

294
00:17:46,081 --> 00:17:47,961
I'll see if there's been
any more reports on that object.

295
00:17:48,081 --> 00:17:50,361
Good, because we need
all the information we can get.

296
00:17:50,481 --> 00:17:51,601
Meet us back here.

297
00:17:51,681 --> 00:17:53,761
GRAHAM: I can have a word
with some of my old pals from work.

298
00:17:53,841 --> 00:17:55,721
I mean, if you want to know what's
happening, ask a bus driver.

299
00:17:55,801 --> 00:17:57,681
-He always says that.
-Yeah, that's because it is true.

300
00:17:57,761 --> 00:17:59,201
I'd still be doing it now if I could.

301
00:17:59,281 --> 00:18:01,321
I can search for weird stuff
on social media.

302
00:18:01,401 --> 00:18:03,321
And I'll check in with my nurses group
on WhatsApp.

303
00:18:03,401 --> 00:18:05,841
-Seriously though, aliens?
-Yup.

304
00:18:05,921 --> 00:18:07,601
Oh, yeah,
maybe I won't mention that bit.

305
00:18:07,681 --> 00:18:08,721
(CHUCKLES)

306
00:18:09,641 --> 00:18:13,361
Suddenly I feel really tired.

307
00:18:13,561 --> 00:18:14,961
That was a big fall you had, love.

308
00:18:15,121 --> 00:18:16,521
Should get you checked out at A&E.

309
00:18:16,681 --> 00:18:19,721
No. I never go anywhere
that's just initials.

310
00:18:19,841 --> 00:18:21,721
(GASPS) Although...

311
00:18:23,441 --> 00:18:25,161
(GROANS) Can one of you catch me?

312
00:18:25,241 --> 00:18:26,521
RYAN: You're going to fall over?

313
00:18:26,601 --> 00:18:28,281
In two minutes, 19 seconds. Wait!

314
00:18:28,361 --> 00:18:29,441
Forget the two minutes.

315
00:18:29,521 --> 00:18:31,881
Nineteen...
Oh, this new nose is so unreliable.

316
00:18:31,961 --> 00:18:32,961
(GASPS)

317
00:18:40,241 --> 00:18:41,921
Yaz, you've done your shift.

318
00:18:42,001 --> 00:18:44,121
Stop pestering
me for more interesting shouts.

319
00:18:44,201 --> 00:18:45,761
It's not that. I'm just wondering

320
00:18:45,841 --> 00:18:48,041
whether there's been anything else
out of the ordinary tonight?

321
00:18:49,041 --> 00:18:52,361
It's the night shift in Sheffield,
everything's out of the ordinary.

322
00:18:57,801 --> 00:19:00,881
I've got to ask you,
any talk of weird stuff

323
00:19:01,121 --> 00:19:03,121
or strange creatures out tonight?

324
00:19:03,881 --> 00:19:06,761
My wife's out with her mates at karaoke,
if that's what you mean.

325
00:19:07,641 --> 00:19:09,801
-(LAUGHING)
-(LAUGHS) Yeah.

326
00:19:25,041 --> 00:19:26,201
-(WHIRRING)
-Ryan.

327
00:19:27,081 --> 00:19:28,201
Look.

328
00:19:38,081 --> 00:19:39,081
Whoa.

329
00:19:42,801 --> 00:19:44,921
She's got two separate pulses.

330
00:19:47,481 --> 00:19:49,361
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

331
00:19:49,561 --> 00:19:50,881
RYAN: Oh, my God. What is that?

332
00:19:51,041 --> 00:19:53,281
GRACE: I have no idea.

333
00:20:06,641 --> 00:20:08,001
(GASPS)

334
00:20:09,241 --> 00:20:10,241
(SHIVERS)

335
00:20:16,281 --> 00:20:17,681
(SIZZLES)

336
00:20:56,561 --> 00:20:58,721
(SCREAMING) Oh!

337
00:20:59,681 --> 00:21:02,161
Who woke me up? I'm not ready.

338
00:21:02,321 --> 00:21:04,281
Still healing. Still... Ahhh!

339
00:21:04,641 --> 00:21:07,281
Can you smell that? No, not smell.

340
00:21:07,601 --> 00:21:09,241
Not hear.

341
00:21:09,361 --> 00:21:10,601
Feel. Can you feel...

342
00:21:11,841 --> 00:21:12,881
Stay still, Ryan.

343
00:21:13,241 --> 00:21:15,241
-What is it? What's the matter?
-(BREATHING HEAVILY)

344
00:21:16,801 --> 00:21:19,441
(EXHALES SHARPLY)
Show me your collarbones.

345
00:21:26,801 --> 00:21:28,921
-Oh, you've all got them.
-So have you.

346
00:21:29,761 --> 00:21:31,841
Yeah, I have. Okay.

347
00:21:32,001 --> 00:21:33,041
(INHALES SHARPLY)

348
00:21:33,121 --> 00:21:35,921
Really sorry. Not good news. DNA bombs.

349
00:21:36,561 --> 00:21:39,041
Microimplants which code to your DNA.

350
00:21:39,121 --> 00:21:42,121
On detonation, they disrupt
the foundation of your genetic code,

351
00:21:42,241 --> 00:21:43,401
melting your DNA.

352
00:21:43,481 --> 00:21:46,921
Fast, and nasty and outlawed
in every civilised galaxy.

353
00:21:47,201 --> 00:21:48,401
How did we get them?

354
00:21:48,481 --> 00:21:49,881
Never mind that,
are they going to go off?

355
00:21:50,041 --> 00:21:52,281
Quiet, I'm trying to think.
It's difficult.

356
00:21:52,361 --> 00:21:54,921
I'm not yet who I am.

357
00:21:56,161 --> 00:21:58,521
Brain and body still rebooting.

358
00:21:58,761 --> 00:22:00,081
Reformatting.

359
00:22:01,241 --> 00:22:03,041
Oh, reformatting!

360
00:22:03,601 --> 00:22:06,001
-Can I borrow that?
-Yeah, I guess so, but what for?

361
00:22:06,201 --> 00:22:08,281
That creature. On the train.

362
00:22:08,401 --> 00:22:10,881
When you two came onboard,
it zapped us all with these.

363
00:22:11,081 --> 00:22:13,481
Simple plan to take out witnesses.
Very clever.

364
00:22:13,601 --> 00:22:15,281
Merciless, but clever.

365
00:22:15,361 --> 00:22:16,401
(MOBILE BEEPING)

366
00:22:16,681 --> 00:22:19,841
-(GASPS) I reformatted your phone.
-No! All my stuff's on there.

367
00:22:20,041 --> 00:22:21,161
-Not anymore!
-(GASPS)

368
00:22:21,321 --> 00:22:23,521
Whoa! Ahhh! (GASPS)

369
00:22:24,561 --> 00:22:26,641
That nap did me the world of good.

370
00:22:27,201 --> 00:22:28,601
Very comfy sofa.

371
00:22:29,961 --> 00:22:30,961
Oh!

372
00:22:33,761 --> 00:22:35,721
Come on. Keep up.

373
00:23:03,041 --> 00:23:04,681
Where's my sister?

374
00:23:12,801 --> 00:23:14,801
Ask me again.

375
00:23:15,601 --> 00:23:17,161
(BREATH TREMBLING)

376
00:23:17,441 --> 00:23:20,241
Where's my sister?

377
00:23:29,281 --> 00:23:30,961
(GASPING)

378
00:23:31,721 --> 00:23:33,361
You will never know.

379
00:23:33,521 --> 00:23:35,201
(WHIMPERING)

380
00:23:35,281 --> 00:23:37,201
(SCREAMING IN AGONY)

381
00:23:53,401 --> 00:23:54,401
-(MOBILE BEEPING)
-Next left.

382
00:23:54,561 --> 00:23:55,761
Where are we driving to?

383
00:23:56,001 --> 00:23:59,601
I reckon she's using my phone to track
the origin signal for the DNA bombs.

384
00:23:59,681 --> 00:24:02,241
-Again, how long until they go off?
-Don't know.

385
00:24:02,321 --> 00:24:05,161
-Well, can't we just defuse 'em?
-Not without the right equipment.

386
00:24:06,721 --> 00:24:08,241
(GASPS) Left again.

387
00:24:08,801 --> 00:24:10,441
(TYRES SCREECH)

388
00:24:13,721 --> 00:24:15,681
(PANTING)

389
00:24:17,001 --> 00:24:19,401
-(MOBILE BEEPING)
-(GASPS) We're close.

390
00:24:19,641 --> 00:24:20,641
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

391
00:24:24,081 --> 00:24:26,241
(ELECTRICITY BUZZING)

392
00:24:32,721 --> 00:24:33,841
(GASPS)

393
00:24:37,281 --> 00:24:39,081
Bingo. Oi!

394
00:24:41,361 --> 00:24:44,081
Oh. I was expecting a tentacley thing.

395
00:24:44,601 --> 00:24:46,121
Don't you move!

396
00:24:48,721 --> 00:24:50,281
Hey, is that another alien?

397
00:24:50,761 --> 00:24:53,361
-Looks like it.
-Why is she running at another alien?

398
00:24:53,441 --> 00:24:54,881
Don't just stand there, come on!

399
00:24:55,001 --> 00:24:56,881
Well... Now you're all running at it.

400
00:24:59,441 --> 00:25:00,481
(PANTING)

401
00:25:02,681 --> 00:25:04,641
Oh! Lost it.

402
00:25:04,721 --> 00:25:05,721
He's fast.

403
00:25:05,881 --> 00:25:10,161
I'm slower because of all this
fizzing inside.

404
00:25:10,241 --> 00:25:11,801
-(PANTING)
-RYAN: In here!

405
00:25:15,041 --> 00:25:16,641
GRAHAM: Got a man down over here.

406
00:25:18,481 --> 00:25:20,801
That thing must have killed him.

407
00:25:20,881 --> 00:25:23,321
I... I've never seen
injuries like these.

408
00:25:23,401 --> 00:25:24,641
Not a weapon blast.

409
00:25:25,841 --> 00:25:27,121
More of an ice burn.

410
00:25:27,201 --> 00:25:29,201
It broke his jaw open, too.

411
00:25:30,121 --> 00:25:32,081
Looks like it took one of his teeth.

412
00:25:32,641 --> 00:25:35,321
What sort of creature kills someone
then stops to pull out a tooth?

413
00:25:36,721 --> 00:25:38,641
I'm sorry you all had to see this.

414
00:25:38,721 --> 00:25:40,961
I'll find something to cover the body.

415
00:25:41,041 --> 00:25:42,601
Thank you, Grace.

416
00:25:44,761 --> 00:25:46,641
DOCTOR: I'm sorry any of this
is happening.

417
00:25:46,721 --> 00:25:49,441
I'm sorry that thing on the train
planted these bombs inside you

418
00:25:49,521 --> 00:25:52,681
and I'm sorry I haven't figured out
what's going on yet.

419
00:25:53,561 --> 00:25:55,681
This is it. This is the thing.

420
00:25:56,481 --> 00:25:58,441
It was all sealed up earlier.

421
00:25:58,521 --> 00:26:00,201
Looks like it's been broken.

422
00:26:00,281 --> 00:26:02,601
Or it's done what it came here for.

423
00:26:03,121 --> 00:26:05,441
Some sort of transport chamber.

424
00:26:05,961 --> 00:26:08,521
Presumably for that thing we just saw
in the alley.

425
00:26:08,601 --> 00:26:10,881
But why here? Why tonight?

426
00:26:13,481 --> 00:26:15,161
Actually, that might have been me.

427
00:26:18,041 --> 00:26:20,761
Why? What did you do.

428
00:26:21,881 --> 00:26:24,881
When I went to get my bike,
there was this line in the air

429
00:26:24,961 --> 00:26:26,801
and then it moved and there were shapes.

430
00:26:27,601 --> 00:26:28,601
And?

431
00:26:29,761 --> 00:26:31,881
-And I touched one.
-Ryan.

432
00:26:32,481 --> 00:26:33,761
You all would have done the same.

433
00:26:33,841 --> 00:26:35,561
-I wouldn't.
-I would have.

434
00:26:36,361 --> 00:26:39,801
All right, the shapes disappeared.
A few seconds later that appeared.

435
00:26:41,641 --> 00:26:42,641
What have I done?

436
00:26:45,281 --> 00:26:46,921
Hard to say, really.

437
00:26:47,121 --> 00:26:49,361
I suppose you'll be blaming this
on the dyspraxia as well.

438
00:26:49,481 --> 00:26:51,481
Can't ride a bike,
started an alien invasion.

439
00:26:51,561 --> 00:26:52,561
-Graham.
-What?

440
00:26:52,641 --> 00:26:55,041
-Enough, love.
-All right, I made a mistake.

441
00:26:55,441 --> 00:26:58,241
But why did that guy move this thing
from the Peaks to here?

442
00:26:58,321 --> 00:27:00,401
And how did he even know
it was there?

443
00:27:01,521 --> 00:27:02,641
Good questions.

444
00:27:05,001 --> 00:27:07,921
Let's take a look around here,
see what we can find.

445
00:27:08,001 --> 00:27:09,161
Can't follow it.

446
00:27:09,241 --> 00:27:12,441
The tracking's been blocked,
like it figured out what I was doing.

447
00:27:12,601 --> 00:27:15,721
If we were tracking bomb signals
from that creature from the train,

448
00:27:16,361 --> 00:27:17,641
why did they lead us here?

449
00:27:18,361 --> 00:27:19,761
Another good question.

450
00:27:20,121 --> 00:27:23,241
I don't know. If I could analyse that...

451
00:27:23,321 --> 00:27:25,001
Course, what I really need is my...

452
00:27:25,081 --> 00:27:26,601
(GROANS)

453
00:27:27,361 --> 00:27:28,961
I could build one!

454
00:27:29,081 --> 00:27:32,281
I'm good at building things. Probably.

455
00:27:42,441 --> 00:27:43,961
It's not your fault, all this.

456
00:27:44,041 --> 00:27:45,401
Yeah, it basically is.

457
00:27:45,481 --> 00:27:47,361
You couldn't have known
that was going to happen.

458
00:27:47,441 --> 00:27:49,161
Maybe tell Graham that.

459
00:27:49,241 --> 00:27:50,801
He knows, really.

460
00:27:58,201 --> 00:27:59,881
Do you believe she's an alien?

461
00:28:01,241 --> 00:28:02,721
Yeah, I think I do, yeah.

462
00:28:03,521 --> 00:28:05,401
-Is that mad?
-No.

463
00:28:06,601 --> 00:28:07,801
I think I do too.

464
00:28:08,081 --> 00:28:09,881
Hey, er, look in here.

465
00:28:30,961 --> 00:28:32,241
Hey, look at this.

466
00:28:40,881 --> 00:28:42,281
You don't look like an alien.

467
00:28:42,641 --> 00:28:44,361
DOCTOR: You should have seen me
a few hours back.

468
00:28:44,441 --> 00:28:45,841
My whole body changed.

469
00:28:46,241 --> 00:28:48,361
Every cell in my body burning.

470
00:28:49,201 --> 00:28:53,281
Some of them are still at it now,
reordering, regenerating.

471
00:28:54,161 --> 00:28:57,761
-Sounds painful, love.
-You have no idea.

472
00:28:58,561 --> 00:29:02,321
There's this moment
when you're sure you're about to die

473
00:29:03,081 --> 00:29:05,801
and then you're born.

474
00:29:06,201 --> 00:29:07,761
-(OBJECTS CLATTER)
-It's terrifying.

475
00:29:09,041 --> 00:29:11,641
Right now I'm a stranger to myself.

476
00:29:12,001 --> 00:29:17,081
There's echoes of who I was
and a sort of call towards who I am.

477
00:29:17,801 --> 00:29:21,961
And I have to hold my nerve
and trust all these new instincts.

478
00:29:22,041 --> 00:29:23,761
Shape myself towards them.

479
00:29:24,841 --> 00:29:27,641
I'LL be fine. In the end.

480
00:29:27,721 --> 00:29:28,721
Hopefully.

481
00:29:28,841 --> 00:29:30,201
-(OBJECT CLATTERS)
-Well, I have to be,

482
00:29:30,281 --> 00:29:32,641
because you guys need help
and if there's one thing I'm certain of,

483
00:29:32,761 --> 00:29:35,121
when people need help, I never refuse.

484
00:29:35,961 --> 00:29:38,361
Right? This is going to be fun.

485
00:30:16,201 --> 00:30:17,361
(GRUNTING)

486
00:30:17,961 --> 00:30:19,721
-(GROANS)
-(ELECTRICITY BUZZING)

487
00:30:29,761 --> 00:30:31,161
-Ta-da!
-(WHIRRING)

488
00:30:31,321 --> 00:30:32,321
Ooh.

489
00:30:32,641 --> 00:30:33,801
Should be fine.

490
00:30:33,881 --> 00:30:36,121
Hey, we found a load of stuff.

491
00:30:40,841 --> 00:30:42,201
It's come back.

492
00:30:43,321 --> 00:30:45,681
(BREATH TREMBLING) The thing I saw
the night my sister...

493
00:30:46,561 --> 00:30:51,281
Everyone always says "disappeared”,
but I know she was taken.

494
00:30:51,801 --> 00:30:53,121
Seven years now.

495
00:30:54,201 --> 00:30:57,641
Tracking energy signals,
building predictive programmes,

496
00:30:57,841 --> 00:31:00,841
so that I'd know when
the atmospheric disruptions

497
00:31:00,921 --> 00:31:02,681
matched what happened that day.

498
00:31:02,761 --> 00:31:05,281
But tonight it came back again

499
00:31:05,361 --> 00:31:06,481
and I've got it.

500
00:31:07,761 --> 00:31:11,161
I am going to find out
what happened to my sister.

501
00:31:12,481 --> 00:31:15,721
If anything happens to me,
her name was Asha.

502
00:31:16,081 --> 00:31:18,241
Don't let anyone else go through this.

503
00:31:20,921 --> 00:31:22,161
-(BREATH TREMBLES)
-(COMPUTER BEEPS)

504
00:31:22,721 --> 00:31:25,161
He knew what he was doing
might kill him.

505
00:31:28,081 --> 00:31:29,761
She was his family.

506
00:31:34,601 --> 00:31:37,001
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)
-Did you just make that?

507
00:31:37,081 --> 00:31:38,361
Sonic screwdriver.

508
00:31:38,441 --> 00:31:41,281
Well, I say screwdriver, but it's a bit
more multi-purpose than that.

509
00:31:41,441 --> 00:31:44,201
Scanner, diagnostics, tin opener.

510
00:31:44,441 --> 00:31:47,681
More of a Sonic Swiss Army knife.

511
00:31:47,841 --> 00:31:50,041
Only without the knife.
Only idiots carry knives.

512
00:31:50,441 --> 00:31:52,161
RYAN: What were you doing with it?

513
00:31:52,401 --> 00:31:54,321
Mapping the distance
this object has travelled.

514
00:31:54,401 --> 00:31:56,601
It looks like it started
over 5,000 galaxies away.

515
00:31:56,921 --> 00:31:58,121
How can you tell?

516
00:31:58,481 --> 00:32:01,201
That bit there. Recall circuitry.

517
00:32:01,321 --> 00:32:02,761
It's designed for a return journey.

518
00:32:02,841 --> 00:32:06,681
So whatever killed that bloke
will have to come back here?

519
00:32:06,881 --> 00:32:09,921
Question is, why did it leave?
What's it looking for?

520
00:32:10,401 --> 00:32:12,401
-GRACE: What's your best guess, love?
-(SIGHS)

521
00:32:12,561 --> 00:32:15,361
Two aliens, one city, one night.

522
00:32:15,841 --> 00:32:19,721
Best guess? Two species at war
using Earth as a battleground.

523
00:32:20,001 --> 00:32:23,081
-Are you joking?
-Nope. Sorry.

524
00:32:23,161 --> 00:32:26,561
So... So you're saying that the creature
on the train

525
00:32:26,641 --> 00:32:27,961
and the thing that come out of here,

526
00:32:28,041 --> 00:32:30,201
they're now looking for each other,
spoiling for a scrap?

527
00:32:30,281 --> 00:32:33,001
-Bit more than a scrap.
-(STAMMERS) What are we going to do?

528
00:32:33,241 --> 00:32:36,961
Because this is my home, and I'm not
having it being an alien battleground.

529
00:32:37,121 --> 00:32:40,081
We stop them meeting, capture them,

530
00:32:40,161 --> 00:32:43,401
send them home, away from each other
and away from Earth.

531
00:32:43,481 --> 00:32:44,641
How do we do that?

532
00:32:44,761 --> 00:32:46,361
Well, give me a minute,
I'm working on it.

533
00:32:46,761 --> 00:32:48,641
Not to sound like a stuck record,

534
00:32:48,801 --> 00:32:50,721
but can I just ask
about these DNA bombs?

535
00:32:50,801 --> 00:32:52,361
Like, how long have we got left?

536
00:32:52,441 --> 00:32:56,481
Enough questions! You lot,
you love to chat, I get it.

537
00:32:56,561 --> 00:32:58,361
Lots to do, I'm working on it all.

538
00:32:58,441 --> 00:33:00,281
And I haven't forgotten
about your collar bones, Graham.

539
00:33:00,361 --> 00:33:01,681
-(MOBILE RINGING)
-Give me nine minutes,

540
00:33:01,761 --> 00:33:03,761
a bit of quiet,
and I'll be ready to roll.

541
00:33:04,601 --> 00:33:07,241
-Scout's honour.
-Hello?

542
00:33:07,801 --> 00:33:09,041
Yeah, Kevin.

543
00:33:09,281 --> 00:33:11,041
No. No, mate.

544
00:33:11,641 --> 00:33:13,281
That's exactly the sort of thing.

545
00:33:18,161 --> 00:33:21,041
No! Nuh-uh.

546
00:33:21,721 --> 00:33:24,601
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

547
00:33:34,881 --> 00:33:36,321
Halloween's next month, mate.

548
00:33:47,161 --> 00:33:48,681
Eat my salad...

549
00:33:49,081 --> 00:33:50,921
Halloween!

550
00:33:54,121 --> 00:33:56,921
(SCREAMING IN AGONY)

551
00:34:19,361 --> 00:34:20,841
Hi. Us again.

552
00:34:24,681 --> 00:34:26,401
-Now!
- (ELECTRICITY BUZZING)

553
00:34:30,281 --> 00:34:31,921
Get in! It actually worked.

554
00:34:32,321 --> 00:34:34,081
Course it worked. I'm not an amateur.

555
00:34:34,201 --> 00:34:36,001
Overloaded its sockets,
stunned it for a bit.

556
00:34:36,081 --> 00:34:37,401
Not sure for how long, though.

557
00:34:37,481 --> 00:34:38,481
Best be quick.

558
00:34:38,561 --> 00:34:41,041
And thank you to Kevin the bus driver

559
00:34:41,121 --> 00:34:43,281
-for location intel.
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

560
00:34:43,361 --> 00:34:44,841
See? Always ask a bus driver.

561
00:34:46,081 --> 00:34:49,601
Half-organic, half-machine.
Starts to make sense now.

562
00:34:49,761 --> 00:34:51,161
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BLEEPING)

563
00:34:51,601 --> 00:34:52,921
Wait.

564
00:34:53,961 --> 00:34:55,561
It's a Gathering Coil.

565
00:34:55,721 --> 00:34:57,681
No, dozens of Gathering Coils!

566
00:34:57,921 --> 00:35:01,481
These tentacley things, they're
creatures which gather information.

567
00:35:01,561 --> 00:35:05,001
They've been lashed together
and augmented into one super-creature.

568
00:35:05,241 --> 00:35:08,521
But why? What data are they gathering?

569
00:35:09,321 --> 00:35:10,321
Unless...

570
00:35:10,721 --> 00:35:12,681
So that's an alien species?

571
00:35:13,081 --> 00:35:14,081
Not really.

572
00:35:14,281 --> 00:35:16,921
More of a semi-species,
weaponised biotech.

573
00:35:17,041 --> 00:35:18,761
You said there were
two aliens in a battle.

574
00:35:19,041 --> 00:35:20,681
You're right, I did,
but now I think I'm wrong

575
00:35:20,761 --> 00:35:23,001
and I'm trying to catch up
with what that might mean.

576
00:35:24,321 --> 00:35:26,361
If I can access
the data it's gathered...

577
00:35:28,961 --> 00:35:30,801
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)
-Whoa!

578
00:35:31,481 --> 00:35:33,361
It's Karl from the train!

579
00:35:33,641 --> 00:35:36,721
DOCTOR: Karl's the data! That's what
it was gathering on the train.

580
00:35:37,121 --> 00:35:38,961
But what would the alien want with him?

581
00:35:39,121 --> 00:35:41,521
WARRIOR: Which one of you
should I kill first?

582
00:35:43,881 --> 00:35:46,281
I'm voting none of us.
Get behind me now.

583
00:35:48,401 --> 00:35:49,481
Stop right there.

584
00:35:49,561 --> 00:35:52,241
Come any further and we'll blast
whatever that thing is.

585
00:35:52,321 --> 00:35:55,161
You're interfering in things
you don't understand.

586
00:35:55,761 --> 00:35:57,441
Yeah, well, we all need a hobby.

587
00:35:57,601 --> 00:36:00,401
You're not human. Who are you?

588
00:36:00,561 --> 00:36:02,441
Me? I'm...

589
00:36:03,361 --> 00:36:05,401
Oh, it's gone again!

590
00:36:05,481 --> 00:36:08,241
I had it a minute ago. It's so annoying!

591
00:36:08,321 --> 00:36:10,281
Same question, back at you.

592
00:36:10,401 --> 00:36:13,321
No, in fact, before that,
because it's really bugging me...

593
00:36:13,401 --> 00:36:15,401
No, actually not bugging me,
offending me!

594
00:36:15,521 --> 00:36:17,441
Why the teeth?

595
00:36:17,521 --> 00:36:20,801
Bad enough you kill,
why take a tooth from the victim?

596
00:36:31,361 --> 00:36:32,601
(SNARLS)

597
00:36:33,441 --> 00:36:37,561
A Stenza warrior wears his conquests.

598
00:36:40,361 --> 00:36:41,801
You may tell your children

599
00:36:41,881 --> 00:36:45,481
you were once privileged to encounter
Tzim-Sha of the Stenza.

600
00:36:47,241 --> 00:36:48,241
Tim Shaw?

601
00:36:49,481 --> 00:36:50,561
Tzim-Sha.

602
00:36:51,281 --> 00:36:52,801
-Tim Shaw?
-Tzim-Sha!

603
00:36:53,521 --> 00:36:56,961
Soon to be leader
of the Stenza warrior race,

604
00:36:57,081 --> 00:36:59,361
Conquerors of the Nine ystems.

605
00:36:59,441 --> 00:37:02,441
When you say "soon to be leader”,
what are you now, the office junior?

606
00:37:02,601 --> 00:37:04,201
GRAHAM: Hey, don't wind him up!

607
00:37:04,321 --> 00:37:06,201
Tonight is my challenge.

608
00:37:07,241 --> 00:37:10,001
Trace and obtain
the selected human trophy.

609
00:37:11,041 --> 00:37:13,401
It's a hunt. You're on a hunt!

610
00:37:13,521 --> 00:37:18,201
Well done. Your tiny mind
must be burning with such effort.

611
00:37:18,601 --> 00:37:20,121
Did he just say I had a small mind?

612
00:37:20,241 --> 00:37:24,441
The challenge is simple, our leaders
randomly designate a selected human.

613
00:37:24,881 --> 00:37:29,881
I'm sent here alone, no weapons,
no assistance.

614
00:37:31,041 --> 00:37:35,561
I must locate and obtain the trophy
and return home with it, victorious.

615
00:37:35,681 --> 00:37:40,041
By doing this, I ascend to leader.

616
00:37:40,761 --> 00:37:42,561
This is the ritual of the Stenza.

617
00:37:43,041 --> 00:37:44,521
This happened before.

618
00:37:45,441 --> 00:37:46,761
Rahul's sister.

619
00:37:46,961 --> 00:37:49,281
Earth is not a hunting ground.

620
00:37:50,041 --> 00:37:51,881
Access was granted.

621
00:37:52,841 --> 00:37:55,521
No, it wasn't.
It was a misunderstanding.

622
00:37:55,641 --> 00:37:58,121
Access revoked, as of now, by me.

623
00:37:58,641 --> 00:38:00,761
Just to pick up on one thing,
you don't mind, do you?

624
00:38:00,841 --> 00:38:05,841
You said the rules were,
"No weapons, no assistance”.

625
00:38:06,121 --> 00:38:08,401
-Correct.
-DOCTOR: How did you kill them?

626
00:38:08,641 --> 00:38:10,201
What caused the ice burns?

627
00:38:10,401 --> 00:38:13,121
We Stenza live in temperatures
far below this planet.

628
00:38:13,241 --> 00:38:16,801
One touch of my cold skin
will kill a human.

629
00:38:17,161 --> 00:38:19,601
So this super-powered Gathering Coil
right here,

630
00:38:19,681 --> 00:38:20,921
you're not meant to have it, are you?

631
00:38:21,241 --> 00:38:24,001
-(GROWLS) The creature is irrelevant.
-DOCTOR: I don't think it is.

632
00:38:24,561 --> 00:38:26,841
I think you smuggled it ahead of you.

633
00:38:27,281 --> 00:38:31,801
I think it located the "randomly
designated human" for you.

634
00:38:32,001 --> 00:38:34,521
I think you broke the rules.

635
00:38:34,961 --> 00:38:36,841
Some leader you're going to make.

636
00:38:37,081 --> 00:38:40,201
Tim Shaw is a big, blue cheat.

637
00:38:42,161 --> 00:38:43,601
Okay, fine, have it.

638
00:38:50,401 --> 00:38:51,601
RYAN: What's it doing?

639
00:38:52,201 --> 00:38:54,361
Total transference.

640
00:38:57,561 --> 00:38:59,401
(ELECTRICITY BUZZING)

641
00:39:02,441 --> 00:39:04,881
DOCTOR: If you've finished,
let's be really clear.

642
00:39:04,961 --> 00:39:07,441
You're not taking any human
from Earth tonight.

643
00:39:07,521 --> 00:39:09,721
Leave now, or we're going to stop you.

644
00:39:10,041 --> 00:39:11,041
Good luck.

645
00:39:11,481 --> 00:39:13,361
(ELECTRICITY SURGING)

646
00:39:13,841 --> 00:39:16,361
No! Short-range teleport! Double cheat!

647
00:39:16,961 --> 00:39:18,441
-(SIGHS)
-Where have they gone?

648
00:39:18,561 --> 00:39:20,481
-To hunt.
-RYAN: Hunt who?

649
00:39:20,721 --> 00:39:21,761
Isn't it obvious?

650
00:39:25,041 --> 00:39:27,961
-WOMAN ON RECORDING: I am special.
-I am special.

651
00:39:28,801 --> 00:39:31,121
-WOMAN: 7 am valued.
-I am valued.

652
00:39:31,481 --> 00:39:36,281
-WOMAN: Somebody out there wants me.
-Somebody out there wants me.

653
00:39:40,161 --> 00:39:41,721
(CRANE WHIRRING)

654
00:39:51,881 --> 00:39:54,641
You stay up too late, madam.

655
00:39:54,721 --> 00:39:58,401
Let your mum get some sleep,
she works very hard for you.

656
00:39:59,241 --> 00:40:02,041
Thank you. I like it that you called me.

657
00:40:02,201 --> 00:40:04,081
Not every granddad's this lucky.

658
00:40:04,161 --> 00:40:05,841
(ELECTRIC WHIRRING)

659
00:40:08,521 --> 00:40:10,321
Daisy, love, I've got to go now.

660
00:40:10,761 --> 00:40:12,041
I love you loads.

661
00:40:12,441 --> 00:40:13,601
(RADIO STATIC)

662
00:40:18,921 --> 00:40:21,201
What do you think you're... (SCREAMING)

663
00:40:36,961 --> 00:40:38,761
Karl's number's
going straight to voicemail.

664
00:40:38,841 --> 00:40:42,441
Got him. Karl Wright,
operator for Skylark Building Services.

665
00:40:42,801 --> 00:40:44,641
I know where their site is.
It ain't far.

666
00:40:44,721 --> 00:40:46,521
Grace, next right, love.

667
00:40:53,281 --> 00:40:54,801
(CRANE WHIRRING)

668
00:40:59,601 --> 00:41:02,881
Dennis, there's someone
climbing up to my cab.

669
00:41:03,761 --> 00:41:05,001
Dennis.

670
00:41:05,641 --> 00:41:06,721
Dennis, it's Karl!

671
00:41:07,801 --> 00:41:09,521
(TYRES SCREECH)

672
00:41:22,161 --> 00:41:24,881
KARL ON: Dennis, I need help!
Somebody's on my crane!.

673
00:41:24,961 --> 00:41:27,401
Oh, great. Karl's a crane operator.

674
00:41:27,521 --> 00:41:28,601
He would be, wouldn't he?

675
00:41:30,161 --> 00:41:31,481
RYAN: It's over there.

676
00:41:31,561 --> 00:41:33,081
That creature's guarding
the bottom of it.

677
00:41:33,481 --> 00:41:35,841
Graham, Grace,
I need you to take this equipment

678
00:41:35,921 --> 00:41:37,041
and get everybody off this site.

679
00:41:37,201 --> 00:41:38,841
Don't care how, use your initiative.

680
00:41:39,161 --> 00:41:41,441
Do not come back in, understand?

681
00:41:42,801 --> 00:41:44,761
Ryan, Yaz,

682
00:41:44,841 --> 00:41:46,961
how are you with machinery

683
00:41:47,041 --> 00:41:48,401
and heights?

684
00:41:55,921 --> 00:41:57,681
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

685
00:41:59,441 --> 00:42:02,921
That tentacley thing is guarding
Karl's crane, so we go up this one.

686
00:42:04,241 --> 00:42:05,641
What do we do when we get up there?

687
00:42:05,761 --> 00:42:07,481
Don't worry, I've got a plan.

688
00:42:07,561 --> 00:42:08,601
Really?

689
00:42:09,041 --> 00:42:11,801
Well, I will have by the time
we get to the top.

690
00:42:17,841 --> 00:42:19,481
Are you all right with this?

691
00:42:19,561 --> 00:42:21,961
Because if it's a problem
you don't have to do it.

692
00:42:22,041 --> 00:42:23,921
I do. I can do this.

693
00:42:31,881 --> 00:42:33,561
Thank you very much.
Total site shutdown.

694
00:42:33,681 --> 00:42:34,921
Quick as you can, please.

695
00:42:35,001 --> 00:42:36,321
Thank you. Major power issues.

696
00:42:36,401 --> 00:42:39,001
Very serious.
Emergency services on the way.

697
00:42:39,121 --> 00:42:41,641
Offsite immediately, please.
Matter of urgency.

698
00:42:44,121 --> 00:42:45,521
You can't come up here.

699
00:42:45,681 --> 00:42:47,161
Turn around, please.

700
00:42:47,841 --> 00:42:50,961
-Go on!
-DOCTOR: Oi! Karl from the train!

701
00:42:52,201 --> 00:42:55,561
Up and over! Up and over!

702
00:42:56,041 --> 00:42:57,521
You have got to be kidding.

703
00:43:01,841 --> 00:43:04,961
I am valued. I am special.

704
00:43:14,121 --> 00:43:16,201
(PANTING)

705
00:43:27,481 --> 00:43:29,921
(GRUNTS)

706
00:43:30,801 --> 00:43:32,721
Ryan, are you okay?

707
00:43:33,001 --> 00:43:34,481
Yeah.

708
00:43:36,441 --> 00:43:38,641
(RYAN BREATHING HEAVILY)

709
00:43:44,761 --> 00:43:47,161
(GRUNTS AND GROANS)

710
00:43:54,161 --> 00:43:56,961
(RADIO STATIC BUZZING)

711
00:43:58,481 --> 00:44:00,481
(METAL SCREECHING)

712
00:44:05,521 --> 00:44:07,561
(GLASS SHATTERS)

713
00:44:10,481 --> 00:44:13,921
I am confident. I achieve my goals.
I achieve my goals.

714
00:44:15,121 --> 00:44:17,441
RYAN: (SCREAMS AND LAUGHS)
Oh, we made it!

715
00:44:17,961 --> 00:44:20,721
Oh! Oh, no, no, no!
It's way too high up here.

716
00:44:20,801 --> 00:44:22,481
What's the plan?
You said you'd have a plan.

717
00:44:22,601 --> 00:44:24,961
Nearly. Nearly, nearly.

718
00:44:26,041 --> 00:44:28,761
I got one. I climb on
to the arm of this crane,

719
00:44:28,841 --> 00:44:31,121
you swing the arm round
next to Karl's crane.

720
00:44:31,201 --> 00:44:32,881
-Oh, no, you're kidding!
-Karl steps across,

721
00:44:32,961 --> 00:44:34,521
you swing the arm my way.

722
00:44:34,601 --> 00:44:37,241
I get him back in here, all back down
for a cuppa and a fried egg sandwich.

723
00:44:37,361 --> 00:44:40,081
I'm really craving a fried egg sandwich.
Simple, no?

724
00:44:40,681 --> 00:44:42,761
-Not really.
-All right. It's a work in progress.

725
00:44:42,841 --> 00:44:44,601
But so is life. It'll be fine.

726
00:44:44,681 --> 00:44:47,441
Ooh, I got these downstairs.
One must work.

727
00:44:47,521 --> 00:44:49,841
You can figure out how to work a crane,
right? Go.

728
00:44:59,601 --> 00:45:01,401
Yup. Way too high.

729
00:45:07,321 --> 00:45:11,401
Grace, she explicitly said
not to come back and it's not safe!

730
00:45:12,201 --> 00:45:14,761
Look, it swapped cranes.
It's trying to bring it down.

731
00:45:15,081 --> 00:45:16,721
-We have to stop it.
-Huh?

732
00:45:18,721 --> 00:45:19,721
Oh!

733
00:45:20,481 --> 00:45:22,481
(GRUNTING)

734
00:45:28,721 --> 00:45:29,721
(GRUNTS)

735
00:45:31,601 --> 00:45:33,441
Last one.

736
00:45:33,521 --> 00:45:35,241
-(MACHINE WHIRRING)
-Get in!

737
00:45:35,321 --> 00:45:36,361
(ALARM SOUNDING)

738
00:45:36,481 --> 00:45:39,321
Okay, now we just need to swing the arm
around to meet that one.

739
00:45:39,401 --> 00:45:41,481
Right, I think this shows us. Ready?

740
00:45:41,761 --> 00:45:43,401
Every day's a learning day.

741
00:45:44,321 --> 00:45:45,721
(CRANE WHIRRING)

742
00:45:46,001 --> 00:45:48,561
Wrong way! Wrong way!

743
00:45:48,921 --> 00:45:49,961
Wrong way. Wrong way!

744
00:45:50,481 --> 00:45:51,561
I know, shut up!

745
00:45:52,281 --> 00:45:53,401
(CRANE WHIRRING)

746
00:46:01,561 --> 00:46:02,921
Higher. Again.

747
00:46:03,321 --> 00:46:04,721
What's going on?

748
00:46:04,921 --> 00:46:08,281
When the arms line up just step across.

749
00:46:08,561 --> 00:46:09,801
(GASPS)

750
00:46:17,681 --> 00:46:19,881
Whoa! Ahhh! Oh.

751
00:46:22,201 --> 00:46:24,641
How am I supposed to get
across there now?

752
00:46:25,561 --> 00:46:30,081
When I said "step”, obviously,
I meant jump. Jump across.

753
00:46:30,321 --> 00:46:32,961
-I can't do that!
-DOCTOR: Of course you can.

754
00:46:33,041 --> 00:46:34,921
Stand up, quick jump.

755
00:46:35,361 --> 00:46:36,961
Chop chop. I'll catch you.

756
00:46:37,121 --> 00:46:39,721
I don't know.
I'm not great with heights.

757
00:46:40,241 --> 00:46:43,161
-What?
-It's my dad's company.

758
00:46:47,641 --> 00:46:48,961
Pop on over.

759
00:46:49,401 --> 00:46:51,521
(PANTING) Okay.

760
00:46:51,881 --> 00:46:54,001
-I am special.
-Yes, you are.

761
00:46:54,201 --> 00:46:55,761
I am brave

762
00:46:57,001 --> 00:46:59,121
and I'm gonna jump!

763
00:46:59,241 --> 00:47:01,921
-No time like the present.
-(WHIMPERS)

764
00:47:07,001 --> 00:47:09,761
(SCREAMS AND GROANS)

765
00:47:13,681 --> 00:47:15,241
Let him go!

766
00:47:16,161 --> 00:47:18,281
(GASPS) I'm sorry.

767
00:47:20,121 --> 00:47:21,641
(GROANS)

768
00:47:22,401 --> 00:47:23,801
If you want something doing.

769
00:47:24,041 --> 00:47:25,641
KARL: Please!

770
00:47:27,681 --> 00:47:28,761
KARL: Help!

771
00:47:32,001 --> 00:47:33,681
ALL: Oh, my God.

772
00:47:38,641 --> 00:47:40,761
(SCREAMS AND GRUNTS)

773
00:47:48,041 --> 00:47:50,321
These legs definitely used to be longer.

774
00:47:51,841 --> 00:47:53,121
(GRUNTS)

775
00:47:55,161 --> 00:47:56,801
(GRUNTS)

776
00:47:57,121 --> 00:47:59,601
(PANTING) Oi! Tim Shaw!

777
00:48:00,041 --> 00:48:01,681
You stop right there.

778
00:48:01,961 --> 00:48:03,441
(GASPING)

779
00:48:12,081 --> 00:48:14,241
Ohh! He's got a face of teeth!

780
00:48:14,321 --> 00:48:16,561
I know. I've got this.

781
00:48:17,201 --> 00:48:20,761
Let him go or I destroy...

782
00:48:20,841 --> 00:48:22,561
this.

783
00:48:23,641 --> 00:48:25,881
(GROANS) I really need a new coat.

784
00:48:26,241 --> 00:48:28,161
(MECHANICAL CLANKING)

785
00:48:29,761 --> 00:48:31,401
-This.
-(DEVICE WHIRRING)

786
00:48:32,321 --> 00:48:34,161
The recall from the pod
you travelled in.

787
00:48:34,881 --> 00:48:36,121
I took it out.

788
00:48:36,201 --> 00:48:38,081
Without this, you can't get home.

789
00:48:39,241 --> 00:48:41,801
Yeah, see? Now you're worried.

790
00:48:43,361 --> 00:48:45,161
If I fall, this falls with me.

791
00:48:46,281 --> 00:48:47,801
Then you're stuck.

792
00:48:51,201 --> 00:48:53,081
-(GRUNTS)
-Yeah?

793
00:48:53,241 --> 00:48:54,721
-Yeah.
-Come on.

794
00:48:56,361 --> 00:48:59,241
What do you do with them,
your human trophies?

795
00:49:00,801 --> 00:49:04,841
They're held in stasis
in our trophy chambers

796
00:49:05,121 --> 00:49:07,601
on the cusp between life and death.

797
00:49:08,001 --> 00:49:09,521
Left to rot?

798
00:49:10,361 --> 00:49:11,961
How completely obscene.

799
00:49:12,241 --> 00:49:13,841
They're not important.

800
00:49:13,961 --> 00:49:16,481
Hey, I'm important.

801
00:49:17,081 --> 00:49:19,561
If I don't stop you,
your people will keep doing this.

802
00:49:20,801 --> 00:49:23,321
-Give me the circuit...
-(DEVICE BEEPS)

803
00:49:23,561 --> 00:49:25,721
...or I detonate the bombs
placed in your friends.

804
00:49:26,241 --> 00:49:27,361
More weapons.

805
00:49:27,601 --> 00:49:29,761
-Did your pet put one in Karl too?
-What?

806
00:49:29,921 --> 00:49:32,321
There was no need. He was tagged.

807
00:49:33,081 --> 00:49:34,681
He is the trophy.

808
00:49:34,761 --> 00:49:37,441
I thought as much.
Right, you detonate the bombs,

809
00:49:38,241 --> 00:49:39,881
I'll destroy the recall.

810
00:49:41,041 --> 00:49:43,921
-So what are we going to do?
-(GRUMBLES)

811
00:49:45,481 --> 00:49:47,001
-(LOCK CLATTERS)
-Right.

812
00:49:47,081 --> 00:49:49,761
You rewired the house, so you sort
things out this end, I'll climb up.

813
00:49:49,921 --> 00:49:51,001
I don't want you doing that.

814
00:49:51,121 --> 00:49:54,121
Graham, Ryan's in danger.
We don't have time to argue.

815
00:49:54,201 --> 00:49:56,081
-Give me the signal when you're ready.
-Okay.

816
00:50:00,921 --> 00:50:02,721
Is it wrong to be enjoying this?

817
00:50:02,801 --> 00:50:05,161
-Yes!
-(LAUGHING)

818
00:50:06,321 --> 00:50:07,321
(EXHALES)

819
00:50:14,681 --> 00:50:16,561
Poor Tim Shaw,

820
00:50:16,801 --> 00:50:20,321
the wannabe leader who has to cheat
because he knows he's unworthy.

821
00:50:20,441 --> 00:50:22,241
See, that's why I know
you won't detonate.

822
00:50:22,681 --> 00:50:24,441
Although, you could prove me wrong.

823
00:50:24,841 --> 00:50:29,001
Because we're all capable
of the most incredible change.

824
00:50:29,881 --> 00:50:34,001
We can evolve while still staying true
to who we are.

825
00:50:34,081 --> 00:50:38,881
We can honour who we've been
and choose who we want to be next.

826
00:50:38,961 --> 00:50:41,081
Now's your chance. How about it?

827
00:50:43,281 --> 00:50:44,881
Who are you?

828
00:50:45,121 --> 00:50:47,521
Oh, yes, I'm glad you asked that again.

829
00:50:47,601 --> 00:50:50,761
Bit of adrenaline, dash of outrage,
and a hint of panic

830
00:50:50,881 --> 00:50:52,601
knitted my brain back together.

831
00:50:53,241 --> 00:50:55,001
I know exactly who I am.

832
00:50:56,201 --> 00:50:57,401
I'm the Doctor.

833
00:50:58,401 --> 00:51:01,201
Sorting out fair play
throughout the universe.

834
00:51:01,281 --> 00:51:06,121
Now, please, get off this planet
while you still have a choice.

835
00:51:07,281 --> 00:51:08,721
I choose to win.

836
00:51:09,321 --> 00:51:10,321
(DEVICE BEEPING)

837
00:51:14,521 --> 00:51:15,521
(ROARS)

838
00:51:18,081 --> 00:51:22,161
Sorry. I removed those nasty little
things from my friends.

839
00:51:22,801 --> 00:51:24,681
-Swiss Army sonic.
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

840
00:51:24,761 --> 00:51:26,841
Now with added Sheffield Steel.

841
00:51:27,601 --> 00:51:29,921
And I implanted them back
in your creature.

842
00:51:31,361 --> 00:51:32,361
(SCREAMING)

843
00:51:32,481 --> 00:51:35,281
Transference wasn't just data,
it was physical.

844
00:51:35,361 --> 00:51:37,521
You got everything transferred to you

845
00:51:37,801 --> 00:51:40,481
including five tiny bombs.

846
00:51:40,961 --> 00:51:43,481
You had a choice.
You did this to yourself.

847
00:51:43,641 --> 00:51:45,001
(SCREAMS)

848
00:51:45,121 --> 00:51:47,081
-Go home.
-(DEVICE WHIRS)

849
00:51:47,401 --> 00:51:49,401
-(GRUNTS)
-(SCREAMS)

850
00:51:55,041 --> 00:51:56,641
I am important!

851
00:51:56,721 --> 00:51:58,441
You had no right to do that.

852
00:51:59,401 --> 00:52:01,001
Put a bomb in me, would you?

853
00:52:03,481 --> 00:52:05,241
GRACE: Now, Graham!

854
00:52:08,321 --> 00:52:09,321
(GROANS)

855
00:52:10,761 --> 00:52:12,201
It's working!

856
00:52:32,001 --> 00:52:34,361
-GRACE: Don't be cross with me.
-I'm not cross, baby.

857
00:52:34,561 --> 00:52:36,041
I'm not cross.

858
00:52:37,361 --> 00:52:39,241
Promise me

859
00:52:40,281 --> 00:52:43,001
-you won't be scared...
-What? What do you mean?

860
00:52:44,361 --> 00:52:46,121
...without me.

861
00:52:49,081 --> 00:52:50,081
Grace.

862
00:52:51,001 --> 00:52:52,441
Grace.

863
00:52:53,601 --> 00:52:54,961
(PANTING)

864
00:53:02,441 --> 00:53:05,121
(GASPS)

865
00:53:15,641 --> 00:53:17,241
RYAN ON COMPUTER: So today
I want to talk about

866
00:53:17,321 --> 00:53:18,801
the greatest woman I ever met.

867
00:53:20,601 --> 00:53:23,641
Smart, funny, caring.

868
00:53:24,601 --> 00:53:25,601
Proper special.

869
00:53:28,281 --> 00:53:29,281
My nan.

870
00:53:31,881 --> 00:53:34,321
Because, er, she died.

871
00:53:39,721 --> 00:53:41,681
First my mum six years ago
and now my nan.

872
00:53:43,681 --> 00:53:45,681
It's like the best people
get taken first.

873
00:53:46,241 --> 00:53:47,841
I had a lot to learn from her.

874
00:53:48,241 --> 00:53:49,721
And I was looking forward to that.

875
00:53:53,841 --> 00:53:56,721
She died like she lived,
trying to help other people.

876
00:53:59,961 --> 00:54:01,401
I love you, Nan.

877
00:54:01,641 --> 00:54:03,121
And tomorrow

878
00:54:03,721 --> 00:54:05,601
I'm going out there for you.

879
00:54:17,841 --> 00:54:19,681
(RYAN GASPS)

880
00:54:20,121 --> 00:54:21,481
(INHALES SHARPLY)

881
00:54:23,281 --> 00:54:24,401
(SIGHS)

882
00:54:28,361 --> 00:54:29,841
(GRUNTS)

883
00:54:33,401 --> 00:54:34,641
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

884
00:54:35,001 --> 00:54:36,161
(GRUNTS)

885
00:54:36,241 --> 00:54:38,601
Three, two, one.

886
00:54:40,041 --> 00:54:41,401
(GROANS)

887
00:54:41,481 --> 00:54:42,561
(SIGHS)

888
00:54:43,681 --> 00:54:44,681
(GRUNTS ANGRILY)

889
00:54:45,281 --> 00:54:46,281
(GRUNTS)

890
00:54:46,601 --> 00:54:47,601
(GRUNTS)

891
00:54:47,801 --> 00:54:49,121
(SIGHS)

892
00:54:50,921 --> 00:54:51,921
(GRUNTS ANGRILY)

893
00:55:17,561 --> 00:55:19,361
What time did your dad say
he'd get here?

894
00:55:19,441 --> 00:55:20,881
Two hours ago.

895
00:55:21,881 --> 00:55:24,201
-If he said he'll come...
-He says a lot of things.

896
00:55:27,201 --> 00:55:29,041
He's never been the best
at being reliable.

897
00:55:35,241 --> 00:55:37,161
I mean, how can he not be here?

898
00:55:38,441 --> 00:55:39,961
She's his mum.

899
00:55:40,761 --> 00:55:42,201
She would have wanted him here.

900
00:55:44,481 --> 00:55:46,161
I want him here.

901
00:55:52,441 --> 00:55:55,601
GRAHAM: Lots of you knew Grace
longer than me,

902
00:55:56,881 --> 00:56:02,041
so I can't stand here and pretend
to know everything about her.

903
00:56:05,401 --> 00:56:07,201
I wasn't her first husband, but,

904
00:56:08,601 --> 00:56:10,761
she said I would do
for a second attempt.

905
00:56:11,121 --> 00:56:12,281
(SCATTERED LAUGHTER)

906
00:56:13,681 --> 00:56:16,881
I can only tell you
about the Grace I met

907
00:56:18,841 --> 00:56:21,361
when I thought I didn't have
much time left.

908
00:56:25,721 --> 00:56:27,201
The, er...

909
00:56:27,801 --> 00:56:30,601
The Grace that showed me life
had more to offer.

910
00:56:31,961 --> 00:56:33,041
And...

911
00:56:36,081 --> 00:56:39,521
And I know that if she was here now
she would tell us not to be so sad.

912
00:56:40,561 --> 00:56:45,201
You see, I can hear her saying to me,
"Graham, we had three glorious years.

913
00:56:47,681 --> 00:56:49,641
"What are you complaining about?"

914
00:56:52,321 --> 00:56:54,321
I'm complaining because I wanted more.

915
00:56:56,081 --> 00:56:58,801
You see, Grace was a better person
than I could ever be.

916
00:57:04,281 --> 00:57:06,601
And I should have gone

917
00:57:08,801 --> 00:57:10,361
and Grace should still be here.

918
00:57:21,001 --> 00:57:25,121
What did you mean in your speech,
you thought you'd "run out of time"?

919
00:57:25,201 --> 00:57:26,801
Oh, well, I, erm...

920
00:57:27,041 --> 00:57:28,881
I had cancer, and, er...

921
00:57:28,961 --> 00:57:32,041
Well, strictly speaking,
I'm still in remission.

922
00:57:32,361 --> 00:57:33,761
Three years gone.

923
00:57:34,601 --> 00:57:39,321
And, er, Grace was my chemo nurse,
that's where we met and fell in love.

924
00:57:40,921 --> 00:57:43,521
So, by rights, I...
I shouldn't even be here.

925
00:57:46,761 --> 00:57:47,921
Have you got family?

926
00:57:50,401 --> 00:57:51,401
No.

927
00:57:52,241 --> 00:57:53,721
Lost them a long time ago.

928
00:57:54,841 --> 00:57:55,961
How do you cope with that?

929
00:57:58,521 --> 00:57:59,961
I carry them with me.

930
00:58:01,241 --> 00:58:04,321
What they would have thought
and said and done.

931
00:58:05,201 --> 00:58:06,841
Make them a part of who I am.

932
00:58:07,161 --> 00:58:10,121
So even though they're gone from
the world, they're never gone from me.

933
00:58:11,441 --> 00:58:13,161
That's the sort of thing
Grace would have said.

934
00:58:15,401 --> 00:58:18,801
So everything we saw,
everything we've lied to people about,

935
00:58:19,761 --> 00:58:21,121
is this normal for you?

936
00:58:22,961 --> 00:58:24,241
I'm just a traveller.

937
00:58:25,201 --> 00:58:27,681
Sometimes I see things need fixin'.

938
00:58:27,761 --> 00:58:29,081
I do what I can.

939
00:58:31,841 --> 00:58:35,761
Except, right now,
I'm a traveller without a ship.

940
00:58:35,841 --> 00:58:37,201
I stayed too long.

941
00:58:37,281 --> 00:58:38,921
I should get back to finding my TARDIS.

942
00:58:39,121 --> 00:58:42,081
Doctor, can I just say

943
00:58:43,241 --> 00:58:44,801
you really need
to get out of those clothes.

944
00:58:47,441 --> 00:58:49,521
-(LAUGHING)
-Right, yeah.

945
00:58:50,281 --> 00:58:52,761
It's been a long time
since I bought women's clothes.

946
00:58:56,721 --> 00:58:58,281
Er, not that.

947
00:58:59,321 --> 00:59:00,481
Not that.

948
00:59:00,881 --> 00:59:01,961
Pfft. Not that!

949
00:59:03,121 --> 00:59:04,561
Ah! Not that.

950
00:59:05,841 --> 00:59:08,681
(GASPS) Yes, now that's what I want!

951
00:59:10,801 --> 00:59:12,081
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

952
00:59:12,561 --> 00:59:13,841
That's what you're going with?

953
00:59:13,921 --> 00:59:15,241
Yup.

954
00:59:15,321 --> 00:59:16,801
Got any cash? Empty pockets.

955
00:59:18,841 --> 00:59:21,481
Also, I've been thinking
about my TARDIS.

956
00:59:21,561 --> 00:59:23,761
Do you think you guys
might be able to help me?

957
00:59:27,201 --> 00:59:28,481
(METALLIC CLANGING)

958
00:59:31,841 --> 00:59:33,641
(OBJECTS CLATTERING)

959
00:59:37,121 --> 00:59:38,401
(WHIRRING)

960
00:59:40,721 --> 00:59:43,401
How long have we got to stand here for?
I'm getting cramp.

961
00:59:43,481 --> 00:59:46,001
Seriously, Graham,
trying to concentrate here.

962
00:59:46,721 --> 00:59:47,961
Do you understand what she's doing?

963
00:59:48,041 --> 00:59:50,361
DOCTOR: My ship uses
a particular type of energy.

964
00:59:50,441 --> 00:59:52,961
I've tracked that energy trail
from the moment I lost it

965
00:59:53,041 --> 00:59:54,161
to where it is now.

966
00:59:54,241 --> 00:59:56,761
Now, given this is a transport pod

967
00:59:56,841 --> 00:59:58,601
-I'm configuring it...
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

968
00:59:58,681 --> 01:00:02,201
...to send me to the planet
where my ship seems to have ended up.

969
01:00:02,481 --> 01:00:04,241
You're going to another planet?

970
01:00:04,321 --> 01:00:07,361
Well, I'm trying to, except
Stenza technology is really annoying

971
01:00:07,601 --> 01:00:09,361
and super hard to decipher.

972
01:00:09,841 --> 01:00:12,601
Hundred and thirty-nine layers,
seven of which don't make sense.

973
01:00:13,121 --> 01:00:15,281
-Right. Graham...
-Yeah?

974
01:00:15,361 --> 01:00:17,281
-Clamp those onto there.
-All right.

975
01:00:18,001 --> 01:00:21,361
Yaz, throw the cable on to the top.
Ryan, you turn on the switch.

976
01:00:21,481 --> 01:00:22,921
-All right.
-(EXHALES)

977
01:00:23,681 --> 01:00:26,801
Okay, you three,
I'm almost going to miss you.

978
01:00:27,801 --> 01:00:29,161
(DEVICE BEEPS)

979
01:00:29,521 --> 01:00:30,521
That's it.

980
01:00:30,641 --> 01:00:31,801
It's connected up.

981
01:00:32,001 --> 01:00:33,001
This should work.

982
01:00:33,321 --> 01:00:34,321
Oh.

983
01:00:37,041 --> 01:00:38,321
Moment of truth, then.

984
01:00:38,961 --> 01:00:40,121
Wish me luck.

985
01:00:42,121 --> 01:00:43,601
(SIGHS)

986
01:00:44,361 --> 01:00:45,561
And goodbye.

987
01:00:48,161 --> 01:00:49,521
(SIGHS) Oh, deep breath.

988
01:00:50,081 --> 01:00:52,561
-(ALL INHALE SHARPLY)
-Not you lot, me.

989
01:00:53,041 --> 01:00:54,201
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

990
01:00:54,361 --> 01:00:56,041
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

991
01:01:02,961 --> 01:01:04,201
(MICROWAVE DINGS)

992
01:01:27,521 --> 01:01:29,201
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

993
01:01:57,841 --> 01:01:59,961
Is anyone excited?
Because I'm really excited.

994
01:02:55,041 --> 01:02:56,801
Right. Let's get a shift on!

